Jupyter Notebook itself is a static documents. ipywidgets allows us to turn it into interactive dashboards. This tutorial just provides some ipywidgets templates you might like.

We’re going to get started by loading up necessary modular and specify some example file in my local computer.

[2]:

%matplotlib inline
import ipywidgets as widgets
from ipywidgets import interactive_output, HBox, VBox
import CactusTool
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

path = '/Users/liuyu/simulations/GW150914/'
sim = CactusTool.load(path)

Scalar¶

[3]:

from CactusTool import TimeSeries

var = sim.Scalar.max[''] # All scalar

def timeseries(Variable, grid):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    ts = TimeSeries(ax, var.dataset)
    ts.plot(Variable)
    if grid:
        plt.grid()
    plt.show()

chapter=widgets.Label(value='CarpetIOScalar:')
var_item=widgets.Dropdown(options=var.dataset.columns[2:], description='Variable:')
grid_item=widgets.Checkbox(value=True, description='Grid')
output = interactive_output(timeseries,
                            {
                                'Variable': var_item,
                                'grid': grid_item
                            })

VBox([
    chapter,
    HBox([
        var_item,
        grid_item
    ]),
    output
])
